==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*huzda-'', from Indo-European ''*kuzdho-'' ‘something hidden, hiding-place’, from ''*keu-, *kewə-'' ‘cover, encase’.  Cognate with Old Saxon ''hord'' ‘treasure, hiding-place’, Old High German [[hort]] (German [[Hort]] ‘hoard, protection, refuge’), Old Norse [[hodd]] (Swedish [[hudda]] ‘shelter’), Gothic [[𐌷𐌿𐌶𐌳]] ‘hidden hoard’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ho:rd/

===Noun===
'''hord''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''hord''')
# a [[hoard]], especially of valuable items, hidden for preservation

